04420nam a22004935i 9780822389859DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20072007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223898597 a10.1515/97808223898592doi  a(DE-B1597)552868  a(OCoLC)1055306955  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aOlwig, Karen Fog, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCaribbean Journeys :bAn Ethnography of Migration and Home in Three Family Networks /cKaren Fog Olwig. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE: A JAMAICAN FAMILY -- t1. Learning to Mix in Society -- t2. Seeking Improvement beyond Jamaica -- tPART TWO: A DOMINICAN FAMILY -- t3. The Village Origins -- t4. In Pursuit of a Proper Livelihood -- tPART THREE: A NEVISIAN FAMILY -- t5. A Family Home -- t6. To Better Our Condition -- tPART FOUR: THE FAMILY LEGACIES -- t7. The First Generation: Migrating for Improvement of Self and the Family -- t8. Generational Perspectives: Negotiating Identities and Origins -- t9. Relating Regional, Family, and Individual Histories of Migration -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCaribbean Journeys is an ethnographic analysis of the cultural meaning of migration and home in three families of West Indian background that are now dispersed throughout the Caribbean, North America, and Great Britain. Moving migration studies beyond its current focus on sending and receiving societies, Karen Fog Olwig makes migratory family networks the locus of her analysis. For the people whose lives she traces, being "Caribbean" is not necessarily rooted in ongoing visits to their countries of origin, or in ethnic communities in the receiving countries, but rather in family narratives and the maintenance of family networks across vast geographical expanses.The migratory journeys of the families in this study began more than sixty years ago, when individuals in the three families left home in a British colonial town in Jamaica, a French Creole rural community in Dominica, and an African-Caribbean village of small farmers on Nevis. Olwig follows the three family networks forward in time, interviewing family members living under highly varied social and economic circumstances in locations ranging from California to Barbados, Nova Scotia to Florida, and New Jersey to England. Through her conversations with several generations of these far-flung families, she gives insight into each family's educational, occupational, and socioeconomic trajectories. Olwig contends that terms such as "Caribbean diaspora" wrongly assume a culturally homogeneous homeland. As she demonstrates in Caribbean Journeys, anthropologists who want a nuanced understanding of how migrants and their descendants perceive their origins and identities must focus on interpersonal relations and intimate spheres as well as on collectivities and public expressions of belonging.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822389859zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822389859423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822389859.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles